				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\log G /R = \log \frac{{\sum I_{\text{hydrophobicity}} }}{{\sum I_{\text{hydrophilicity}} }}$$\end{document}where G and R represent the hydrophobic potential (green) and hydrophilic potential (red) for each SAS point, and I is the intensity of hydrophobic/hydrophilic potential.

Then, with a linear regression analysis between logG/R and logP values of these 41 GNPs, the following equation was generated and can be used to calculate nanologP (i.e. logP values of GNPs) values for new GNPs from their logG/R results, which were obtained from vGNP simulations:2nanologP=0.7334∗logG/R-2.4306\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
